xt\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test coverage and structure**\\n\\nI'm noticing issues around test coverage for dynamic-access classes, such as ensuring each has its dedicated test file — there's a ClassReloadingStrategyTest, which is good. I'm considering the one-to-one mapping between report classes and test files; we only have the active class for now. I see that public access is required for top-level classes, while Byte_buddyTest is a non-public issue. I'm also weighing dependencies, like possibly needing `testRuntimeOnly` instead of `testImplementation`. There’s some concern about method visibility and blank lines in Checkstyle too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering import practices in Java and Groovy**\\n\\nI’ve identified a potential issue regarding the importation of classes in Java and Groovy. We're importing ClassReloadingStrategy but using the qualified name for its nested Strategy. I could import `net.bytebuddy.dynamic.loading.ClassReloadingStrategy.Strategy` and use `Strategy.REDEFINITION`, which aligns with the guideline to avoid qualified names. While existing tests mostly use `ByteArrayClassLoader.ChildFirst` without importing it directly, I’m wondering if importing Strategy could make the code more idiomatic and easier to read, even if it isn’t strictly necessary.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_WYgBjhT1uOcc5SoGDy0VGAJF|fc_0ef5232842737908016a102599a28881a2adc9ebfd4caca4a3", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/net.bytebuddy/byte-buddy/1.8.15/src/test/java/net_bytebuddy/byte_buddy/ClassReloadingStrategyTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import net.bytebuddy.dynamic.loading.ClassReloadingStrategy;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\n", "newText": "import net.bytebuddy.dynamic.loading.ClassReloadingStrategy;\nimport net.bytebuddy.dynamic.loading.ClassReloadingStrategy.Strategy;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\n"}, {"oldText": "            ClassReloadingStrategy reloadingStrategy = ClassReloadingStrategy.fro